A polyprenylhydroquinone consisting of hydroquinone in which the hydrogen at position 2 is substituted by a (2<stereo>E</stereo>)-3,7-dimethylocta-2,6-dien-1-yl group.

Water-soluble anionic substituted thioglucosides. Glucosinolates have a central C atom which is bonded via an S atom to a glycone group and via an N atom to a sulfonated oxime group, and which also carries a side-group. The side-chain and sulfate group have an <stereo>anti</stereo> stereochemical configuration across the C<bond>2</bond>N double bond.
The glucosyl group formed from <stereo>D</stereo>-glucopyranose.
A monosaccharide derivative that is anthracene-9,10-dione substituted by a <stereo>beta</stereo>-<stereo>D</stereo>-glucopyranosyloxy group at position 1.
A pentenedioic acid that is pent-2-ene substituted by carboxy groups at positions 1 and 5.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide that is formally derived from glutaric acid by conversion of one of the two carboxylic acid groups to the corresponding amide.
A monophosphoglyceric acid having the phospho group at the 2-position.

An <element>N</element>-nitro compound that is 1,3,5-triazinane in which all three of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogens have been replaced by nitro groups. It is widely used in both industrial and military explosives.
A diol that consists of a cyclohexane skeleton carrying two hydroxy substituents.
An alkene that is hexane carrying a double bond at position 1.

A methanesulfonate salt resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of hycanthone and methanesulfonic acid. It was formerly used as a schistosomicide for individual or mass treatement of infection with <ital>Schistosoma haematobium</ital> and <ital>S. mansoni</ital>, but due to its toxicity and concern about possible carcinogenicity, it has been replaced by other drugs such as praziquantel.
Nuclear particle of charge number +1, spin <frac12/> and rest mass of 1.007276470(12) u.
Benzenediols that have the hydroxy substituents in the 1- and 4-positions.
A member of the class of  hydroxyindoles that is 1<element>H</element>-indole substituted by a hydroxy group at position 4.
A streptomycin bearing an additional hydroxy substituent at the 5'-position (on the furanose ring)
A chlorine oxoacid with formula HOCl; a weak, unstable acid, it is the active form of chlorine in water.
The hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 3-(imidazol-5-yl)lactic acid.

Compounds having the structure RN=CR<smallsub>2</smallsub> (R = H, hydrocarbyl). Thus analogues of aldehydes or ketones, having NR doubly bonded to carbon; aldimines have the structure RCH<bond>2</bond>NR, ketimines have the structure R'<smallsub>2</smallsub>C<bond>2</bond>NR (where R' is not H). Imines include azomethines and Schiff bases. Imine is used as a suffix in systematic nomenclature to denote the C<bond>2</bond>NH group excluding the carbon atom.
A dicarboxylic acid dianion resulting from the removal of a proton from both of the carboxy groups of iminodiacetic acid.
An amino dicarboxylic acid that is glycine in which one of the hydrogens attached to the nitrogen is substituted by a carboxymethyl group.
A glucosinolate that is the conjugate base of indolylmethylglucosinolic acid.
An indole-3-carboxylic acid carrying a carboxy group at position 3.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid that is lactic acid substituted by a 1<element>H</element>-indol-3-yl group at position 3. It is a metabolite of tryptophan.
An indolyl alcohol carrying a hydroxymethyl group at position 3. It is a constituent of the cruciferous vegetables and had anticancer activity.
Any cyclohexane-1,2,3,4,5,6-hexol.
Chemical element with atomic number 53.
Oximes of ketones R<smallsub>2</smallsub>C<bond>2</bond>NOH (where R <notequal/> H).
A C<smallsub>18</smallsub>, 5,6-allenic fatty acid.
A hydroxy monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of lactic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
